- 'Peak thermometer rise' refers to the maximum temperature for the day;
- 'Heart of the city' refers to the area with the zip code '10001';
- 'Exceptional quality' indicates a data quality score greater than 90;
- 'Notably high' humidity means the average humidity is greater than 50%.

- "Bask in the glory of the sun" refers to areas with high average maximum temperatures;
- "Ranking among the top 5" indicates the highest five values when sorted in descending order;
- "Cities and states" are derived from the zip codes with the highest average maximum temperatures.

- "average mean temperature" refers to the average of the mean temperatures recorded;
- "maximum maximum temperature" refers to the highest maximum temperature recorded;
- "minimum minimum temperature" refers to the lowest minimum temperature recorded;
- "population over 10,000" means the city has more than 10,000 residents.

- 'High-quality' refers to data with a quality score above 90;
- 'Temperate breezes' refer to average wind speeds;
- 'Partly cloudy skies' refer to average cloud cover;
- 'Comfortable 50 degrees Fahrenheit or more' refers to the average temperature being greater than 50 degrees Fahrenheit;
- 'In 2022' refers to data recorded during the year 2022.

- The average maximum temperature is calculated for each city and year;
- The ranking is done within each year, separately for each city;
- Only the top 3 cities are selected for each year.

- "Top 5 zip codes" refers to the zip codes with the highest average maximum temperatures and highest average mean humidities over the analyzed period;
- "Average maximum temperature" and "average maximum humidity" are calculated based on daily averages for each zip code and date;
- "Specific dates" are the dates within the dataset where the weather data was collected.

- "pockets of land (zip codes)" refers to specific geographic areas identified by zip codes;
- "enough observations to tell a stormy tale" means there are more than 10 data entries;
- "most consistent gusts of wind, measured by their average speed" refers to the average mean wind speed;
- "strongest gusts noted" refers to the maximum wind speed.

- 'Blooming with temperatures' refers to zip codes with average temperatures higher than the overall average for California;
- 'Dawn of 2020' refers to the date January 1, 2020;
- 'State's average warmth' is the average mean temperature across all zip codes in California after January 1, 2020.

- The 'average temperature' is calculated as the mean of the maximum, mean, and minimum temperatures in Fahrenheit for each weather data entry;
- The 'quality score' is a measure of the reliability or accuracy of the weather data, ranging from 0 to 100;
- The population of a zip code is the total number of people living in that area.

- "Population of at least 10,000" implies a threshold for considering a zip code as significant in this context;
- "Average maximum temperature" is calculated by averaging the maximum temperatures recorded over a period for each zip code;
- "Overall average maximum temperature" is the average of all maximum temperatures across all zip codes.
